Prompt: Terraform for IPv6-only EC2 Kubernetes Dev Setup (AWS, ap-south-1)

I want Terraform code to provision a minimal, learning-focused AWS infrastructure for running a single-node Kubernetes cluster on an IPv6-only EC2 instance. This is for personal development and interview-prep learning, not production. Please keep this deliberately simple — do not over-engineer it. No unnecessary modules, no multi-AZ, no managed Kubernetes service, no extra abstraction layers. I'd rather have a small number of flat, readable .tf files than a deeply nested module structure.

Goal of the setup

A single EC2 instance, reachable only over public IPv6 (no public IPv4, no Elastic IP, no NAT Gateway), running a lightweight single-node Kubernetes cluster (k3s) with an ingress controller bound to the instance's public IPv6 address. API Gateway (created separately, not in scope here) will later point an HTTP_PROXY integration directly at this instance's public IPv6 address.

Required components — and nothing beyond this

VPC

A single dual-stack VPC (IPv4 CIDR required by AWS even though we won't use IPv4 publicly, plus an Amazon-provided /56 IPv6 CIDR block).
One IPv6-only public subnet, carved as a /64 from the VPC's IPv6 block, in a single Availability Zone (no need for multiple AZs or multiple subnets).

Internet Gateway

Attached to the VPC.

Route table

A single route table for the subnet with:

::/0 → Internet Gateway (IPv6 default route)
No IPv4 default route needed since there's no NAT Gateway and no public IPv4 use.

Security Group

Inbound: SSH (port 22) restricted to my IP (use a variable for my_ip_cidr, IPv6 form), and the ingress controller port (443, and optionally 80) open to ::/0.
Outbound: allow all.
Keep this to one security group — no separate SGs per concern.

EC2 instance

Launched into the IPv6-only subnet, with ipv6_address_count = 1 (or equivalent), and explicitly no public IPv4 address assigned.
Use a Nitro-based instance type (e.g. t4g.small or t3.small — prefer Graviton/t4g if available in ap-south-1 for cost efficiency, otherwise fall back to t3.small).
Use the latest Ubuntu 24.04 LTS or Amazon Linux 2023 AMI (your choice, pick whichever has simpler IPv6 metadata/userdata support).
Attach the security group above.
User data script should:

Enable IMDSv2 with IPv6 metadata access (the fd00:ec2::254 endpoint).
Install k3s in single-node mode (curl -sfL https://get.k3s.io | sh -) with flags needed for IPv6-only operation (cluster CIDR / service CIDR set to IPv6 ranges, disable the default servicelb if we're binding ingress directly via hostPort/hostNetwork).
Install a lightweight ingress controller (NGINX ingress is fine) configured to run with hostNetwork: true so it binds directly to the node's public IPv6 address, rather than provisioning a cloud load balancer.

No Auto Scaling Group, no Launch Template complexity — a plain aws_instance resource is sufficient since this is a single fixed node.

IAM

Minimal instance role/profile only if strictly needed for the user data script to function (e.g. SSM access for debugging via Session Manager instead of relying solely on IPv6 SSH). Skip IAM entirely if not needed.

Outputs

The instance's public IPv6 address (for use in the API Gateway HTTP_PROXY integration later).
The instance ID.

Explicitly out of scope — do not add these

No EKS, no managed control plane.
No NAT Gateway, no Elastic IP, no public IPv4 anywhere.
No multi-AZ, no high availability, no Auto Scaling.
No remote state backend setup (S3/DynamoDB) — local state is fine for this.
No Terraform modules/submodules — flat root-level .tf files (main.tf, variables.tf, outputs.tf) are sufficient.
No extra observability stack, no Prometheus/Grafana, no Helm charts beyond the one ingress controller install via user data — keep this purely infra provisioning.
No service mesh, no Kafka, no managed databases — this is just the compute + networking shell described above.

Other requirements

Target region: ap-south-1 (Mumbai).
Use Terraform AWS provider, pinned to a recent stable version.
Keep variable definitions minimal — only what's genuinely needed (region, instance type, my IP CIDR for SSH, key pair name).
Add brief inline comments explaining each IPv6-specific choice (why no NAT, why no public IPv4, why the route table only has an IPv6 default route), since this is for learning and I want to understand each decision, not just copy-paste working code.
After generating the code, briefly explain the apply order / any manual steps (e.g. key pair creation) needed before running terraform apply.